[{"id":30781,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Concentration of calcium lactate =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>005</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p>concentration of lactate ion =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>005</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p>Calcium lactate is a salt of weak acid + strong base</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;Salt hydrolysis will take place for a basic salt:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>pKa</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>logC</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>log</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>)</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>85</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30798,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#8652;</mo><msup><mi>Zn</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>(</mo><mi>aq</mi><mo>)</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>18</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>18</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30819,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2.22</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>18</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>18</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>4.86</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>29</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mi>C</mi><mi>r</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>O</mi><mi>H</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi><msup><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>O</mi><msup><mrow></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>.</mo><mi></mi><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>S</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>  <br/><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>  <br/><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>27</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>  <br/><math><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>O</mi><msup><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>s</mi></math>  <br/><math><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>27</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>18</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mi>M</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30807,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ClF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Lewis base: Chemical species which has capability to donate electron pair.</p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>ClF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> central atom (i.e. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math>)<br />having lone pair therefore act as Lewis base.</p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PCl</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;central atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfenced></math> does not have lone pair therefore does not act as Lewis base.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30764,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Precipitation when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi><mrow></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Reaction quotient, it is the ratio of products to reactants at any time of reaction.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math>Solubility product.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mg</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>⇋</mo><msup><mi>Mg</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>Mg</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>pOH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>  </mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mi>pH</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30852,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{BaSO}_4>\\mathrm{Hg}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}_2>\\mathrm{Cr}_2\\left(\\mathrm{SO}_4\\right)_3>\\mathrm{CrCl}_3$","$\\mathrm{BaSO}_4>\\mathrm{Hg}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}_2>\\mathrm{CrCl}_3>\\mathrm{Cr}_2\\left(\\mathrm{SO}_4\\right)_3$","$\\mathrm{BaSO}_4>\\mathrm{CrCl}_3>\\mathrm{Hg}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}_2>\\mathrm{Cr}_2\\left(\\mathrm{SO}_4\\right)_3$","$\\mathrm{Hg}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}_2>\\mathrm{BaSO}_4>\\mathrm{CrCl}_3>\\mathrm{Cr}_2\\left(\\mathrm{SO}_4\\right)_3$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$$\n\\text { } \\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{Cr}_2\\left(\\mathrm{SO}_4\\right)_3 \\leftrightharpoons 2 \\mathrm{Cr}^{+++}+3 \\mathrm{SO}_4^{--} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=(2 s)^2(3 s)^3=4 \\mathrm{~s}^2 \\times 27 s^3=108 s^5 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{~s}=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{s p}}{108}\\right)^{1 / 5} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{Hg}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}_2 \\leftrightharpoons 2 \\mathrm{Hg}^{2+}+2 \\mathrm{Cl}^{-} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=(2 s)^2 \\times(2 s)^2=16 s^4 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{~s}=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{s p}}{16}\\right)^{1 / 4} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{BaSO}_4 \\leftrightharpoons \\mathrm{Ba}^{++}+\\mathrm{SO}_4^{-} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=s^2 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{~s}=\\sqrt{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{CrCl}_3 \\leftrightharpoons \\mathrm{Cr}^{3+}+3 \\mathrm{Cl}^{-} \\\\\n& s\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=s \\times(3 s)^3=27 s^4 \\\\\n& s=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{s p}}{27}\\right)^{1 / 4}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nHence the correct order of solubilities of salts is\n$$\n\\sqrt{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}}>\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}}{16}\\right)^{1 / 4}>\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}}{27}\\right)^{1 / 4}>\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}}{108}\\right)^{1 / 5}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30771,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["Both <strong>Statement-I</strong> and <strong>Statement-II</strong> are incorrect","<strong>Statement-I</strong> is incorrect but <strong>Statement-II</strong> is correct","Both <strong>Statement-I</strong> and <strong>Statement-II</strong> are correct","<strong>Statement-</strong>I is correct but <strong>Statement-II </strong>is incorrect"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Methyl orange is a weak acid. Additionally, in acidic conditions, methyl orange exists in the quinonoid form, which is red in color. In alkaline conditions, it exists in the benzenoid form, which is yellow in color.&nbsp;Since red is more deeply coloured than yellow, Statement-2 is wrong.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/df1104fa-43df-4eb0-8873-6750cb3acdbd-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 216px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30859,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$3 \\times 10^{-1}$","$1 \\times 10^{-3}$","$1 \\times 10^{-5}$","$1 \\times 10^{-7}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]=\\sqrt{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\cdot \\mathrm{C}} \\Rightarrow 10^{-3}=\\sqrt{\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}} \\cdot 10^{-1}}$\n$\\Rightarrow \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{a}}=10^{-5}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":30777,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Mole of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>69</mn></mrow><mn>23</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#10230;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Number of moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Na</mi></math> = Number of moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>NaCl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>Moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>&nbsp;= moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mtext>Molarity</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi>HCl</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></math>Number of moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mn>73</mn><mrow><mn>36</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Lit</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30879,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["not a buffer solution with pH  < 7","not a buffer solution with pH > 7","a buffer solution with pH  < 7","a buffer solution with pH > 7"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":30862,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$4.1 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{M}$","$5.1 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{M}$","$8.1 \\times 10^{-8} \\mathrm{M}$","$8.1 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{M}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{Ba}\\left(\\mathrm{NO}_3\\right)_2+\\mathrm{CaCO}_3 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{BaCO}_3+2 \\mathrm{NaNO}_3 \\\\\n& \\text { Here }\\left[\\mathrm{CO}_3^{-2}\\right]=\\left[\\mathrm{Na}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3\\right]=10^{-4} \\mathrm{M} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{sp}}=\\left[\\mathrm{Ba}^{+2}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{CO}_3^{-2}\\right] \\Rightarrow 5.1 \\times 10^{-9}=\\left[\\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}\\right]\\left(10^{-4}\\right) \\Rightarrow\\left[\\mathrm{Ba}^{+2}\\right]=5.1 \\times 10^{-5}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nAt this value, just precipitation starts.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":30810,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Ionic Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><m